      "altText": "Typical application schematic for the LT7153SP configured as a 0.5V, ±25A buck regulator with input voltage range of 2.7V to 5V.",
      "imageDescription": "The schematic shows the LT7153SP in a complete buck regulator application with VIN ranging from 2.7V to 5V connected to the SW and PV_IN pins. Input and output bulk capacitors are shown along with an output inductor. Key configuration pins including RUN, FB, PGOOD, MODE, SYNC/SPREAD, RT, ITH, SGND, AVPSEL, CLKOUT, TRACKSS, PHSMOD2/LIM, PHSMOD1/SEL are labeled. A 4.7µF bypass capacitor is shown on the INT_VCC pin, and resistors on RT and ITH set switching frequency and compensation. The output is labeled VOUT = 0.5V at ±25A.",
      "docOrder": 0
    }
  ],
  "figures": [
    {
      "type": "pinConfiguration",
      "figure": 3,
      "altText": "Top-view pin configuration diagram of the LT7153SP in a 36-lead LQFM package (4mm x 7mm x 1.02mm), showing all pin numbers and signal names arranged around the IC perimeter.",
      "imageDescription": "The diagram shows the LT7153SP IC in top-view orientation with pins numbered 1 through 41 (including corner and exposed pad pins). Left-side pins (1-12, 39) carry signals INTV_CC and SW (switching node) pins along with GND. Right-side pins (19-30, 40-41) carry PV_IN, SYNC/SPREAD, SV_IN, CLKOUT, and GND signals. Top pins (31-38) include SGND, RT, ITH, TRACK/SS, FB, VOUT-, and GND. Bottom pins (13-18) include RUN, AVPSEL, PHSMD1/ISEL, PHSMD2/ILIM, MODE, and PGOOD. Pin 37 is the central exposed pad connected to GND, and corner pins 38-41 are also GND and must be soldered to the PCB.",
      "docOrder": 0
    },
    {
      "type": "blockDiagram",
      "figure": 26,
      "altText": "Block diagram of the LT7153SP switching regulator IC showing internal functional blocks including gate drive, oscillator, error amplifier, track amplifier, LDO, on-time calculator, current comparators, and power good status logic with all external pin connections labeled.",
      "imageDescription": "The block diagram illustrates the complete internal architecture of the LT7153SP synchronous buck controller. Key functional blocks include MTOP and MBOT gate drivers fed by a GATEDRIVE block with a BOOST bootstrap capacitor, a REVERSE CURRENT COMPARATOR and CURRENT COMPARATOR for inductor current sensing via ISEL/ILIM, an OSCILLATOR controlled by SYNC/SPREAD, MODE, PHSMD1, PHSMD2, and RT pins with a CLK_INT output feeding an ON-TIME CALCULATOR. The feedback path includes an ERROR AMPLIFIER with FB and ITH pins, a TRACK AMPLIFIER with TRACK/SS and INTERNAL SS inputs referenced to a 0.5V source, and a THERMAL SHUTDOWN LOGIC block. External pins shown include PV_IN, GND, SV_IN, RUN, INTV_CC, V_OUT, CLKOUT, PGOOD, AVPSEL, SW, and BOOST, with decoupling capacitors of 0.2µF and 0.1µF indicated at appropriate nodes.",
      "docOrder": 1
    },
    {
      "type": "circuit",
      "figure": 27,
      "altText": "Resistive voltage divider feedback network for setting the output voltage of the LT7153SP regulator. R1 and R2 form a divider between VOUT and GND, with the FB pin sensing the midpoint and an optional feedforward capacitor CFF placed in parallel with R1.",
      "imageDescription": "The schematic shows the LT7153SP IC block with FB and GND pins connected to an external resistive divider. R1 is connected between VOUT and the FB pin, while R2 is connected between the FB pin and the Kelvin to POL GND node. An optional feedforward capacitor CFF is shown in parallel with R1, connected between VOUT and the FB node. The GND pin of the IC connects to the Kelvin to POL GND reference point.",
      "docOrder": 2
    },
    {
      "type": "blockDiagram",
      "figure": 28,
      "altText": "Multiphase configuration timing diagrams showing phase relationships for 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, and 12-phase operation of LT7153SP regulators. Each sub-diagram illustrates the phase offsets between internal oscillator, CLKOUT, and SYNC signals.",
      "imageDescription": "The figure contains six sub-diagrams (labeled 1 through 6) depicting chain-style timing/phase relationship diagrams for 2, 3, 4 (two variants), 6 (two variants), 8, and 12-phase multiphase configurations. Each node in the chain represents a phase angle value in degrees, with arrows labeled with incremental phase offsets (e.g., +180, +120, +90, -60, -45, -30, -90) connecting successive phase nodes. Some configurations include external clock (EXT CLK) input variants. The 12-phase diagram is the most complex, showing multiple parallel chains with nodes at 0, 180, 300, 60, 150, 330, 30, 120, 240, 210, 90, and 270 degrees. The diagrams collectively illustrate how multiple LT7153SP devices are chained and offset to achieve interleaved multiphase operation.",
      "docOrder": 3
    },
    {
      "type": "circuit",
      "figure": 29,
      "altText": "External compensation network for the ITH pin of the LT7153SP, consisting of R_ITH in series with C_ITH to ground, and a parallel bypass capacitor C_ITHP to ground.",
      "imageDescription": "The schematic shows the ITH pin connected to a series resistor R_ITH, followed by a node connecting to capacitor C_ITH to ground. A separate bypass capacitor C_ITHP is connected in parallel from the ITH pin node to ground. The network forms a dominant pole-zero RC compensation structure for the OPTI-LOOP feedback control. Component labels R_ITH, C_ITH, and C_ITHP are indicated with standard schematic symbols.",
      "docOrder": 4
    },
    {
      "type": "circuit",
      "figure": 30,
      "altText": "Top layer PCB design example for the LT7153SP showing the component placement area of 2.5cm x 1.3cm highlighted in red, alongside the bottom layer view of the evaluation board.",
      "imageDescription": "The left image shows a green PCB top layer with a red rectangle highlighting the core power stage area measuring 2.5cm x 1.3cm, containing the LT7153SP IC (U1), inductor (L1), and surrounding passive components including input/output capacitors labeled C_IN, C_OUT, and CVCC. Component reference designators visible include C17, C29, C30, C40, and others arranged around the central IC. The right image shows the bottom (primary side) of the same evaluation board with a red PCB finish, displaying the solder mask side with visible vias, copper pours, and component pads. The board label reads '03-088276 REV 2 SINGLE PRIMARY SIDE' on the bottom layer image. Both images together illustrate the recommended board layout for proper thermal and electrical performance.",
      "docOrder": 5
    },
    {
      "type": "circuit",
      "figure": 31,
      "altText": "Schematic of a 0.875V/25A, 2MHz step-down converter using LT7153SP with 1% load line regulation. Shows single-phase buck converter with feedback resistor divider R1 (7.5kΩ) and R2 (10kΩ), 36nH inductor, and output capacitors.",
      "imageDescription": "Single-phase step-down converter circuit using the LT7153SP IC with input voltage range of 2.7V to 5V and output of 0.875V at 25A. Input side shows 47µF×2 capacitors and 47nF capacitor. The SW pin connects through a 36nH inductor to the output node with 100µF×2 and 220µF×2 output capacitors. Feedback network uses R1=7.5kΩ and R2=10kΩ resistors. Compensation network on ITH pin includes 50kΩ, 2kΩ resistors and 10pF, 4.7nF capacitors. A 10µF capacitor is connected to INTVcc and SGND pins.",
      "docOrder": 6
    },
    {
      "type": "circuit",
      "figure": 32,
      "altText": "Schematic of a high efficiency dual-phase 0.5V/50A, 2MHz step-down converter using two LT7153SP ICs in interleaved configuration. Combined output delivers 50A with 100µF×4 and 470µF×2 output capacitors.",
      "imageDescription": "Dual-phase interleaved buck converter using two LT7153SP ICs, each handling one phase with a 36nH inductor, operating at 2MHz switching frequency. Input voltage is 2.7V to 5V and output is 0.5V at 50A total. Each phase has 47µF×2 input capacitors; the output stage shares 100µF×4 and 470µF×2 capacitors. The master phase (top IC) has a compensation network with 50kΩ, 1kΩ resistors and 10pF, 10nF capacitors; the slave phase (bottom IC) has 50kΩ resistor and 10pF capacitor. CLKOUT of the master connects to SYNC/SPREAD of the slave for phase interleaving, and both PGOOD signals are tied together.",
      "docOrder": 7
    },
    {
      "type": "pinConfiguration",
      "altText": "Table 4 showing Multiphase Pin Configuration for the LT7153SP, specifying PHSMD1 and PHSMD2 pin voltage settings and their resulting phase degrees for SYNC-to-Oscillator and Oscillator-to-CLKOUT relationships.",
      "imageDescription": "Table 4 is a two-section table titled 'Multiphase Pin Configuration.' The first section covers the SYNC to Oscillator phase relationship (phi_SYNC to OSC), listing six combinations of PHSMD1 and PHSMD2 voltage levels (0, INTVcc, INTVcc/2) and corresponding phase offsets in degrees (0, 0, -30, -45, -60, -90). The second section covers the Oscillator to CLKOUT phase relationship (phi_OSC to CLKOUT), listing the same six PHSMD1/PHSMD2 combinations with resulting phase offsets (180, 120, 180, 180, 120, 180 degrees). Both sections use degree as the unit for phase values.",
      "docOrder": 8
    }
  ],
  "equations": [
    {
      "latex": "f_{SW}",
      "lhs": "f_{SW}",
      "description": "Represents the switching frequency variable of a power converter.",
      "sectionRef": "Programming Switching Frequency",
      "surroundingText": "Connecting a resistor, R RT , from the RT pin to SGND programs the switching frequency,  , from 400kHz to 5MHz according to the following formula:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "f_{SW}(\\text{Hz}) = \\frac{1\\text{e}^{11}}{R_{RT}(\\Omega)}",
      "lhs": "f_{SW}",
      "description": "Calculates the switching frequency in Hz as a function of the timing resistor R_RT in ohms.",
      "sectionRef": "Programming Switching Frequency"
    },
    {
      "latex": "V_{OUT} = 0.4\\text{V}^{*} \\cdot \\left(1 + \\frac{R1}{R2}\\right)",
      "lhs": "V_{OUT}",
      "description": "Calculates the output voltage using the reference voltage and a resistor divider ratio.",
      "sectionRef": "Output Voltage Programming",
      "surroundingText": "Each regulator’s output voltage is set by an external resistive divider according to the following equation:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "T_{SS} = 0.4^{*} \\cdot e^{5} \\cdot C_{SS}",
      "lhs": "T_{SS}",
      "description": "Calculates the soft-start time period as a function of the soft-start capacitor C_SS.",
      "sectionRef": "Soft-Start and Output Voltage TRACK",
      "surroundingText": "An internal 10µA pulls up the TRACK pin to INTV cc . Putting an external capacitor, C SS , from TRACK to ground enables soft starting the output to prevent a current surge on the input supply. The relationship between output rise time, T SS , and soft-start capacitance, C SS , is given by:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\Delta I_{L} = \\frac{V_{OUT}}{f_{SW} \\cdot L} \\cdot \\left(1 - \\frac{V_{OUT}}{V_{IN}}\\right)",
      "lhs": "\\Delta I_{L}",
      "description": "Calculates the peak-to-peak inductor current ripple based on output voltage, switching frequency, inductance, and duty cycle.",
      "sectionRef": "Inductor Selection",
      "surroundingText": "For a given input voltage,  V IN , output voltage, V OUT , the inductor value, L, and operating frequency, f, determine the ripple current:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "L = \\frac{V_{OUT}}{f_{SW} \\cdot \\Delta L_{(MAX)}} \\cdot \\left(1 - \\frac{V_{OUT}}{V_{IN(MAX)}}\\right)",
      "lhs": "L",
      "description": "Calculates the minimum inductance required to limit the peak-to-peak current ripple at maximum input voltage.",
      "sectionRef": "Inductor Selection",
      "surroundingText": "A reasonable starting point is to choose a ripple current that is about 40% of I OUT(MAX) . Exceeding 60% of I OUT(MAX)  is not recommended. Note that the largest ripple current occurs at the highest  V IN . To guarantee that ripple current does not exceed a specified maximum, the inductance should be chosen according to:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "I_{L(PEAK)} = I_{OUT(MAX)} + \\frac{\\Delta I_{L}}{2}",
      "lhs": "I_{L(PEAK)}",
      "description": "Calculates the peak inductor current as the sum of maximum output current and half the inductor current ripple.",
      "sectionRef": "Inductor Selection",
      "surroundingText": "To avoid overheating and poor efficiency, choose an inductor with an RMS current rating that is greater than the maximum expected output load of the application. In addition, the saturation current (typically labeled I SAT ) rating of the inductor must be higher than the load current plus 1/2 of inductor ripple current:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "I_{RMS} \\cong I_{OUT(MAX)} \\cdot \\frac{V_{OUT}}{V_{IN}} \\cdot \\sqrt{\\frac{V_{IN}}{V_{OUT}} - 1}",
      "lhs": "I_{RMS}",
      "description": "Approximates the RMS input current of a buck converter as a function of output current, output voltage, and input voltage.",
      "sectionRef": "Input Capacitor (CIN) Selection",
      "surroundingText": "The input capacitance, C IN , is needed to filter the square wave current at the drain of the top power MOSFET. To prevent large voltage transients from occurring, use a low ESR input capacitor sized for the maximum RMS current. The maximum RMS current is given by:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "I_{RMS} \\cong \\frac{I_{OUT}}{2}",
      "lhs": "I_{RMS}",
      "description": "Approximates the RMS capacitor current as half the output current.",
      "sectionRef": "Input Capacitor (CIN) Selection",
      "surroundingText": "This formula has a maximum at V IN  = 2V OUT , where:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\Delta V_{OUT} < \\Delta I_{L} \\cdot \\left(\\frac{1}{8 \\cdot f_{SW} \\cdot C_{OUT}} + \\text{ESR}\\right)",
      "lhs": "\\Delta V_{OUT}",
      "description": "Defines the condition for output voltage ripple as a function of inductor current ripple, switching frequency, output capacitance, and ESR.",
      "sectionRef": "Output Capacitor (COUT) Selection",
      "surroundingText": "The selection of C OUT  is determined by the effective series resistance (ESR) that is required to minimize voltage ripple and load step transients, as well as the amount of bulk capacitance that is necessary to ensure that the control loop is stable. Loop stability can be checked by viewing the load transient response. The output ripple, ∆V OUT , is determined by:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "C_{OUT} = 3 \\cdot \\left(\\frac{\\Delta I_{OUT}}{f_{O} \\cdot V_{DROOP}}\\right)",
      "lhs": "C_{OUT}",
      "description": "Calculates the required output capacitance based on load current step, crossover frequency, and allowable voltage droop.",
      "sectionRef": "Output Capacitor (COUT) Selection",
      "surroundingText": "Since the ESR of a ceramic capacitor is so low, it is more useful to choose the output capacitor value to fulfill a charge storage requirement. During a load step, the output capacitor must instantaneously supply the current to support the load until the feedback loop raises the switch current enough to support the load. The time required for the feedback loop to respond is dependent on the compensation and the output capacitor size. Typically, five cycles are required to respond to a load step, but only in  the first cycle does the output voltage drop linearly. The output droop, V DROOP , is usually about three times the linear drop of the first cycle. Thus, a good place to start with the output capacitor value is approximately."
    },
    {
      "latex": "V_{IN(MIN)} = V_{OUT} \\cdot \\frac{t_{ON} + t_{OFF(MIN)}}{t_{ON}}",
      "lhs": "V_{IN(MIN)}",
      "description": "Calculates the minimum input voltage based on output voltage and the ratio of on-time plus minimum off-time to on-time.",
      "sectionRef": "Minimum Off-Time and Minimum On-Time Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "The minimum off-time, t OFF(MIN) , is the smallest amount of time that the LT7153SP is capable of turning on the bottom power MOSFET, tripping the current comparator and turning the power MOSFET back off. This time is generally about 30ns. The minimum off-time limit imposes a maximum duty cycle of t ON /(t ON  + t OFF(MIN) ). If the maximum duty cycle is reached due to a dropping input voltage, for example, then the output drops out of regulation. The minimum input voltage to avoid dropout is:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "DC_{(MIN)} = f_{SW} \\cdot t_{ON(MIN)}",
      "lhs": "DC_{(MIN)}",
      "description": "Calculates the minimum duty cycle as the product of switching frequency and minimum on-time.",
      "sectionRef": "Minimum Off-Time and Minimum On-Time Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "Conversely, the minimum on-time is the smallest duration of time in which the top power MOSFET can be in its ON state. This time is typically 15ns. In continuous mode operation, the minimum on-time limit imposes a minimum duty cycle of"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\%\\text{Efficiency} = 100\\% - (L1 + L2 + L3 + \\ldots)",
      "lhs": "",
      "description": "Estimates converter efficiency by subtracting the sum of all loss terms from 100%.",
      "sectionRef": "Efficiency Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "The percent efficiency of a switching regulator is equal to the output power divided by the input power times 100%. It is often useful to analyze individual losses to determine what is limiting the efficiency and which change produces the most improvement. Percent efficiency can be expressed as:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "R_{SW} = R_{DS(ON)TOP}(DC) + R_{DS(ON)BOT}(1 - DC)",
      "lhs": "R_{SW}",
      "description": "Calculates the effective switch resistance as the duty-cycle-weighted sum of top and bottom MOSFET on-resistances.",
      "sectionRef": "Efficiency Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "I 2 R losses are calculated from the DC resistances of the internal switches, R SW , and external inductor, R L . In continuous mode, the average output current flows through inductor L but is chopped between the internal top and bottom power MOSFETs. Thus, the series resistance looking into the SW pin is a function of both top and bottom MOSFET R DS(ON)  and the duty  cycle (DC) as follows:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "I^{2}R \\text{ losses} = I_{OUT}^{2} \\cdot (R_{SW} + R_{L})",
      "lhs": "",
      "description": "Calculates the total I²R conduction losses due to switch resistance and inductor DCR.",
      "sectionRef": "Efficiency Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "The R DS(ON)  for both the top and bottom MOSFETs can be obtained from the Typical Performance Characteristics curves. Thus to obtain I 2 R losses:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\text{Switching Loss} = I_{GATECHG} \\cdot P V_{IN}",
      "lhs": "",
      "description": "Calculates the switching power loss as the product of gate charge current and input voltage.",
      "sectionRef": "Efficiency Considerations",
      "surroundingText": "The switching current is the sum of the MOSFET driver and control currents. The power MOSFET driver current results from switching the gate capacitance of the power MOSFETs. Each time a power MOSFET gate is switched from low to high to low again, a packet of charge dQ moves from  P V IN   to ground. The resulting dQ/dt is a current out of IN that is typically much larger than the DC control bias current. In continuous mode, I GATECHG  = f(Q T  + Q B ), where Q T  and Q B  are the gate charges of the internal top and bottom power MOSFETs, and f is the switching frequency. The power loss is thus:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "10\\mu\\text{A} = C_{SS} \\cdot \\frac{0.875\\text{V}}{4\\text{ms}}",
      "lhs": "",
      "description": "Relates the soft-start charging current to the soft-start capacitor and the required voltage ramp rate.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "For a typical soft-start time of 4ms (0% to 100% of final V OUT  value), the C SS  should be:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "L = \\frac{V_{OUT}}{f_{SW} \\cdot \\Delta L_{(MAX)}} \\cdot \\left(1 - \\frac{V_{OUT}}{V_{IN(MAX)}}\\right)",
      "lhs": "L",
      "description": "Calculates the required inductance to achieve a specified maximum current ripple at maximum input voltage.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "Because efficiency is important at both high and low load current, discontinuous mode operation is utilized. Select from the characteristic curves the correct R T  resistor for the 2MHz switching frequency. Based on that, R RT  should be 50k Ω . Then calculate the inductor value to achieve a current ripple that is about 40% of the maximum peak current limit (25A) at maximum V IN :"
    },
    {
      "latex": "L = \\frac{0.875\\text{V}}{2\\text{MHz} \\cdot 10\\text{A}} \\cdot \\left(1 - \\frac{0.875\\text{V}}{5\\text{V}}\\right) = 36\\text{nH}",
      "lhs": "L",
      "description": "Calculates a numerical example of the inductor value yielding 36 nH for a 0.875 V output at 2 MHz switching frequency with 10 A ripple and 5 V input.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\Delta V_{OUT} < \\Delta I_{L} \\cdot \\left(\\frac{1}{8 \\cdot f_{SW} \\cdot C_{OUT}} + \\text{ESR}\\right)",
      "lhs": "\\Delta V_{OUT}",
      "description": "Specifies the condition that output voltage ripple must be less than the inductor current ripple multiplied by the capacitor impedance and ESR.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "Select C OUT  based on the ESR that is required to satisfy the output ripple requirement and the bulk capacitance needed for loop stability. For this design, use two 100µF and two 220µF ceramic capacitors."
    },
    {
      "latex": "I_{RMS} \\cong I_{OUT(MAX)} \\cdot \\frac{V_{OUT}}{V_{IN}} \\cdot \\text{Sqrt}\\left(\\frac{V_{IN}}{V_{OUT}} - 1\\right)",
      "lhs": "I_{RMS}",
      "description": "Approximates the RMS input capacitor current as a function of maximum output current, output voltage, and input voltage.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "Size C IN  for a maximum current rating of:"
    },
    {
      "latex": "I_{RMS} = 25\\text{A}",
      "lhs": "I_{RMS}",
      "description": "States a specific numerical result of 25 A for the RMS current.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "•(0.875V/5V) •"
    },
    {
      "latex": "\\left((5\\text{V}/0.875\\text{V}) - 1\\right)^{\\frac{1}{2}} = 9.5\\text{A}",
      "lhs": "",
      "description": "Evaluates the square root expression used in the RMS current calculation for given input and output voltages, yielding 9.5 A.",
      "sectionRef": "Design Example",
      "surroundingText": "•(0.875V/5V) •"
    }
  ],
